### ============================================================================
### service-policy — FULL LIFECYCLE walkthrough (create → version → activate →
### evaluate → deactivate), with request AND response contracts for each step.
###
### Open in VS Code (REST Client) or IntelliJ HTTP Client; run top-down.
### Start the app first:  ./mvnw quarkus:dev    (Docker running for MongoDB + OIDC)
### Swagger UI: http://localhost:8080/q/swagger-ui   OpenAPI: /q/openapi
###
### Tokens (ADR-013):
###   {{admin_jwt}} — token satisfying the admin marker (default role "authz-admin").
###                   Required for all policy writes.
###   {{jwt}}       — any valid authenticated token. Used for evaluation.
###   See "How to obtain tokens" at the bottom.
###
### KEY CONCEPTS you'll exercise:
###   - Everything is nested under the application: /v1/apps/{app}/… (ADR-026).
###     The PATH is the single source of scope — `app` must NOT appear in any request
###     body (sending it → 400, even if it matches the path).
###   - Identity is COMPOSITE (app, policyId): "doc-access" can exist in `rh` AND in
###     `nami` at the same time. They are two different policies.
###   - `resourceType` is a per-app namespace: use "document", never "rh:document".
###   - The app must DECLARE the actions of a resource type before any policy about it
###     can be authored (ADR-028) — step 0 below. `actions: ["*"]` is expanded against
###     that catalogue AT AUTHORING and the explicit list is stored; `*` never reaches
###     storage or the evaluator. See action-catalogue.http for the full surface.
###   - Create leaves the policy INACTIVE. It is NOT evaluable until activated.
###   - Versions are append-only (PUT adds v2, v3…); you activate an EXPLICIT version.
###   - Writes are conditional: If-Match: "<revision>" (the ETag from a GET).
###       Stale ETag → 412 ; missing If-Match → 428.
###   - The listing shows ALL lifecycle states by default (ADR-025); ?status= filters.
###   - Errors are RFC 9457 application/problem+json (see docs/ERRORS.md).
### ============================================================================

@host = http://localhost:8080
@auth_admin = Bearer {{admin_jwt}}
@auth = Bearer {{jwt}}


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 0) DECLARE the action catalogue of "document" in app "rh" (ADR-028)  →  201
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Without this, every create below fails with 400 INVALID_POLICY: "no action
### catalogue for resource type 'document' in this app; declare the catalogue before
### authoring". Declare the vocabulary first, then write policies about it.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["create", "read", "update", "delete"]
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created, ETag: "1"
### The same declaration is needed in app "nami" before step 11.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1) CREATE a policy in app "rh"  →  201 Created, INACTIVE
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Note: NO "app" field in the body — the path carries it.
### `actions: ["*"]` is SUGAR: it is expanded against the step-0 catalogue and what
### gets PERSISTED is ["create","read","update","delete"] (verify in step 5). Adding a
### verb to the catalogue later will NOT widen this policy — that needs a new version.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "doc-access",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "assigned-access", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "IN",
        "left": {"ref": "subject.id"}, "right": {"ref": "resource.attr.assignees"} } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created
### { "policyId": "doc-access", "version": 1, "active": false }


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2) LIST the app's policies — the INACTIVE one is visible by default (ADR-025)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK   (Paginated<PolicyHeadSummary>)
### {
###   "data": [
###     { "policyId": "doc-access", "app": "rh", "resourceType": "document",
###       "activeVersion": null,      ← inactive, and still listed
###       "revision": 0, "audit": {…} }
###   ],
###   "pagination": { "page": 1, "size": 20, "totalPages": 1, "totalElements": 1 }
### }
### `app` IS returned in responses (the server supplies it) — it is only absent from
### request bodies.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3) GET the policy  →  200, read the ETag (needed to write)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK.  Headers: ETag: "0"
### Body (PolicyHeadView): { policyId, app:"rh", resourceType, activeVersion:null,
###                          revision:0, audit:{…}, activeContent:null }


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4) APPEND a new version (PUT)  →  200, creates v2 (still inactive)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "0"

{
  "content": {
    "policyId": "doc-access",
    "version": 2,
    "resourceType": "document",
    "actions": ["*"],
    "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
    "defaultEffect": "DENY",
    "rules": [
      { "id": "assigned-access", "effect": "PERMIT",
        "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "IN",
          "left": {"ref": "subject.id"}, "right": {"ref": "resource.attr.assignees"} } },
      { "id": "area-scope", "effect": "PERMIT",
        "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
          "left": {"ref": "resource.attr.area"}, "right": {"ref": "subject.attr.area"} } }
    ]
  },
  "changeReason": "add area-scope rule"
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "1"   (activeVersion still null — append does not activate)


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5) LIST versions
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/versions?view=full
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — data: [ {policyId, app:"rh", version:1, …}, {… version:2 …} ]
### Look at `actions` in the content: ["create","read","update","delete"] — NOT ["*"].
### That is ADR-028 expansion at authoring; `*` is gone by the time anything is stored.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 6) EVALUATE before activating  →  200 allowed:false (nothing active yet)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Evaluation is nested too. NO "app" in the body.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": {"assignees": ["test-user"]}}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  { "allowed": false, "policyVersion": null, … }


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 7) ACTIVATE version 2  →  200, now it's live
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/activate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "1"

{
  "version": 2,
  "changeReason": "go live with area-scope"
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "2"   (activeVersion: 2)


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 8) EVALUATE — PERMIT (subject is an assignee)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Replace "test-user" with the sub in your {{jwt}}.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": {"assignees": ["test-user"]}}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: true, policyVersion: "2"


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 9) EVALUATE — PERMIT via area-scope (v2's new rule)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d2", "attributes": {"area": "A"}},
  "subjectAttributes": {"area": "A"}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: true


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 10) EVALUATE — DEFAULT DENY (nothing matches)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d4", "attributes": {"assignees": ["someone-else"], "area": "B"}},
  "subjectAttributes": {"area": "A"}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: false (defaultEffect DENY)


### ============================================================================
### COMPOSITE IDENTITY (ADR-026) — the SAME policyId in a DIFFERENT app
### This is what R026 fixed: it used to be rejected with a misleading
### "app is immutable" error. Now they coexist as two independent policies.
### ============================================================================

### 11a) The catalogue is per-app too — nami must declare its own vocabulary first.
### Note it need not match rh's: two apps may both define "document" with different
### verbs and never collide (ADR-024/026/028).
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["read", "update"] }

### EXPECTED  201 Created — the same resourceType in another app is a DIFFERENT entry.


### 11) Create "doc-access" AGAIN — but in app "nami"  →  201 (not 409!)
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "doc-access",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "clearance-gate", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
        "left": {"ref": "resource.attr.clearanceLevel"}, "right": {"value": 5} } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created — SAME policyId, DIFFERENT app → a different policy.
### Identity is (app, policyId). Also note the same resourceType "document" — a per-app
### namespace, so no collision (ADR-024).


### 12) Each is read under its own route — they are independent
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/policies/doc-access
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — app: "nami", its own rules, its own revision (0), inactive.
### The rh one is untouched (still active on v2).


### 13) Activate the nami one
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/policies/doc-access/activate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "0"

{ "version": 1 }

### EXPECTED  200, ETag: "1"


### ============================================================================
### APPLICATION ISOLATION (ADR-024) — a policy never decides another app's request
### ============================================================================

### 14) The rh request, evaluated under app "nami" → DENIED
### Same body as step 8 (which PERMITs under rh). Only the path changes.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": {"assignees": ["test-user"]}}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: FALSE
### The rh policy is INVISIBLE to app nami. Only nami's policy applies, and its
### clearance rule does not match → defaultEffect DENY.


### 15) The nami request, evaluated under app "rh" → DENIED
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d9", "attributes": {"clearanceLevel": 5}}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: FALSE  (nami's policy is invisible to rh)


### 16) …and under its own app, it PERMITs
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d9", "attributes": {"clearanceLevel": 5}}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: TRUE


### ============================================================================
### CROSS-APP CATALOGUE (ADR-026 §3) — read-only, for multi-app administrators
### ============================================================================

### 17) All policies of ALL apps (paginated server-side)
GET {{host}}/v1/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — both "doc-access" of rh AND "doc-access" of nami, each with its
### own `app` field. This is the only non-nested route, and it is READ-ONLY.


### 18) Catalogue filtered by app
GET {{host}}/v1/policies?app=rh
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — only rh's policies


### 19) Catalogue filtered by status
GET {{host}}/v1/policies?status=active
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — only active heads, across all apps


### 20) COMPOSITION — app AND status (filters combine with AND)
GET {{host}}/v1/policies?app=rh&status=active
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — only the ACTIVE policies of app rh


### ============================================================================
### NESTED LISTING FILTERS — ?status= still applies inside an app
### ============================================================================

### 21) Only the inactive policies of app "rh"
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies?status=inactive
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 — inactive heads of rh only.  (There is no ?app= here — the path
### already scopes it.)


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 22) DEACTIVATE  →  200, soft retire (history intact)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/deactivate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "2"

{ "changeReason": "temporarily retire" }

### EXPECTED  200, ETag: "3".  activeVersion: null (versions are kept)


### 23) EVALUATE after deactivate  →  allowed:false
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": {"assignees": ["test-user"]}}
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: false


### ============================================================================
### ERROR CONTRACTS — RFC 9457 application/problem+json (docs/ERRORS.md)
### ============================================================================

### 24) 400 INVALID_POLICY — `app` present in the body (ADR-026)
### Even though it MATCHES the path, the field must not exist at all.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "policyId": "with-app-in-body",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": []
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "INVALID_POLICY"
### → "'app' must not be present in the body; it is determined by the path."
### A contradicting value (e.g. "app":"nami" here) gives the same 400 — the field is
### rejected for EXISTING, so a body can never silently override the route.


### 25) 400 BAD_REQUEST — `app` present in an evaluation body
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d1"}
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "BAD_REQUEST"
### (Same for EVERY item of /evaluate/batch — one offending item fails the whole batch.)


### 26) 409 POLICY_ALREADY_EXISTS — duplicate id WITHIN the same app
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "doc-access",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": []
}

### EXPECTED  409  code: "POLICY_ALREADY_EXISTS"
### → "A policy with id 'doc-access' already exists in app 'rh'."
### The 409 is now per-app and honest: the same id in ANOTHER app is fine (step 11).


### 27) 404 POLICY_NOT_FOUND — the policy of another app is invisible
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/policies/doc-access
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  404  code: "POLICY_NOT_FOUND"
### → "No policy with id 'doc-access' in app 'kronia'."
### It exists in rh and nami, but not in kronia. Identity is (app, policyId).


### 28) 428 PRECONDITION_REQUIRED — write without If-Match
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "content": { "policyId": "doc-access", "version": 4, "resourceType": "document",
    "actions": ["*"], "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES", "defaultEffect": "DENY",
    "rules": [] },
  "changeReason": "no if-match" }

### EXPECTED  428  code: "PRECONDITION_REQUIRED"


### 29) 412 PRECONDITION_FAILED — stale If-Match
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/activate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "0"

{ "version": 1 }

### EXPECTED  412  code: "PRECONDITION_FAILED"  (extension: currentRevision)


### 30) 404 VERSION_NOT_FOUND — activate a version that doesn't exist
### Use the current ETag of rh/doc-access in place of "3".
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/activate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "3"

{ "version": 99 }

### EXPECTED  404  code: "VERSION_NOT_FOUND"


### 31) 400 — invalid ?status= value
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies?status=whatever
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  400  → "'status' must be one of: active, inactive, all."
### NOTE: ?status= (present but EMPTY) is also 400 — a blank value is an explicit
### invalid value, not an absence.


### 32) 400 INVALID_POLICY — ordering operator with a non-numeric LITERAL (ADR-023)
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "bad-typed",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "bad", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "GT",
        "left": {"ref": "subject.attr.clearance"}, "right": {"value": "abc"} } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "INVALID_POLICY"
### NOTE (ADR-023): a non-numeric LITERAL is rejected at authoring. A non-numeric
### ATTRIBUTE resolved at runtime is NOT an error — the comparison just doesn't hold
### → deny. Evaluation never returns 500 on operand type.


### 33) 403 FORBIDDEN — write with a non-admin token
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "policyId": "nope", "version": 1, "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES", "defaultEffect": "DENY", "rules": [] }

### EXPECTED  403  code: "FORBIDDEN"  (caller lacks the admin marker)


### ============================================================================
### CLEANUP — there is no hard delete by design (soft retire only).
### To reset in dev, drop the Mongo collections or use fresh policyIds.
### ============================================================================

### ============================================================================
### HOW TO OBTAIN TOKENS (dev)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### In quarkus:dev the OIDC dev services start a Keycloak. Get tokens via the Dev UI
### (http://localhost:8080/q/dev) → OIDC. {{admin_jwt}} must carry the admin marker
### (role "authz-admin" by default; configurable per ADR-013).
###
### SURFACE (ADR-026):
###   /v1/apps/{app}/policies[/{id}[/activate|/deactivate|/versions[/{v}]]]
###   /v1/apps/{app}/policies:simulate
###   /v1/apps/{app}/action-catalogue[/{resourceType}]   ← ADR-028, see action-catalogue.http
###   /v1/apps/{app}/evaluate[/batch]
###   /v1/apps/{app}/permissions
###   /v1/policies                    ← cross-app catalogue, READ-ONLY (?app= ?status=)
###
### POLICY AUTHORING REFERENCE:
###   Identity     (app, policyId). The app comes from the PATH; `app` must NOT be in
###                the body (400 if present, even if it matches).
###   resourceType Per-app namespace: "document", NOT "rh:document".
###   actions      Must all be in the app's catalogue for that resourceType (ADR-028);
###                ["*"] expands to the whole catalogue AT AUTHORING and is never
###                stored. An unknown verb, or a "*" mixed with a verb, → 400.
###   Operators:   EQ, NEQ, IN, NOT_IN, GT, GTE, LT, LTE
###   Operands:    {"ref": "<path>"}  paths: subject.id | subject.attr.* |
###                resource.type | resource.id | resource.attr.* | context.*
###            or  {"value": <literal>}
###   Composites:  {"type": "and"|"or", "conditions": [ … ]}
###   Ordering ops (GT/GTE/LT/LTE) require numeric operands (ADR-023).
### ============================================================================
